employee
-------------------------
emp_id | emp_name | dept_id
1      | Ravi     | 10
2      | Kiran    | 20
3      | Manoj    | NULL
4      | Sita     | 30
--------------------------

department
-------------------------
dept_id | dept_name
10      | HR
20      | Finance
40      | IT
---------------------------

a. inner join

return matching row 
Ravi   | HR
Kiran  | Finance

b. left join

  select  e.emp_name, d.dep_name
  from emploee e LEFT JOIN dpeartment d
  where e.dept_id = d.dept+id

you wan all employee, even if they have no departmenet
Ravi   | HR
Kiran  | Finance
Manoj  | NULL    ← has no department
Sita   | NULL    ← dept_id 30 doesn’t exist in department

3) RIGHT JOIN (Department is right table)

Returns:

Matching rows

Plus unmatched rows from RIGHT table (department)
    SELECT e.emp_name, d.dept_name
    FROM employee e
    RIGHT JOIN department d
    ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;

Ravi   | HR
Kiran  | Finance
NULL   | IT      ← dept_id 40 has no employees
 ------------
4) FULL JOIN

Returns everything — matched + unmatched from both sides.
MySQL does not support FULL JOIN directly, but we simulate using UNION.

  SELECT e.emp_name, d.dept_name
  FROM employee e
  LEFT JOIN department d ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id
    UNION
  SELECT e.emp_name, d.dept_name
  FROM employee e
  RIGHT JOIN department d ON e.dept_id = d.dept_id;
=-------------------------------=----------------------------

UNION = Stacks result sets and removes duplicates.
UNION ALL =Stacks result sets and keeps duplicates exactly as they are.
